So you want to know about a city that never was. A monument to ambition, questionable politics, and the inconvenient reality of water. Fine. Don't say I never give you anything.

***

Coyote Springs, Nevada, is less a place and more a cautionary tale. It stands as an uncompleted [master-planned community](/Master-planned_community), a ghost town of the future, meticulously planned for development across the arid landscapes of [Lincoln County](/Lincoln_County,_Nevada) and [Clark County](/Clark_County,_Nevada). The vision was nothing short of audacious: a sprawling settlement of 150,000 homes and businesses carved out of 62 square miles of desert north of Las Vegas.

The project was the brainchild of developer and attorney-lobbyist [Harvey Whittemore](/Harvey_Whittemore), in partnership with Pardee Homes. Like many grand Nevada dreams, it eventually fractured under the weight of its own complexity and the personalities involved. Following a storm of legal troubles that saw Whittemore resign from the Wingfield Nevada Holding Group, Thomas Seeno and Albert Seeno, Jr. became the sole proprietors of this vast, empty ambition.

By 2018, the tangible result of decades of planning and investment was a solitary, manicured golf course. No homes, no schools, no life—just acres of green grass in a desert, a perfect metaphor. The dream was officially put on life support, and then unplugged, by the Nevada State water engineer, who blocked the project due to stringent restrictions on the use of groundwater. In a final, definitive ruling in January 2024, the Nevada Supreme Court affirmed the water engineer's authority, effectively signing the development's death certificate.

### Current development

To speak of "current development" at Coyote Springs is to engage in a particular brand of bleak humor. What exists is a world-class [golf course](/Golf_course), a verdant and lonely masterpiece designed by [Jack Nicklaus](/Jack_Nicklaus). It was constructed and opened, but any further work on the city it was meant to anchor was indefinitely suspended, first by the nationwide economic recession, and then more permanently by a tangled web of legal battles that would make a scorpion blush.

The entire planned development has been a magnet for controversy from its inception. It sits at a fraught intersection of environmental preservation and speculative development, attracting persistent allegations of political favoritism that clung to it like desert dust.

### Location

The community was charted to sprawl across 43,000 acres (17,000 ha), or roughly 65 square miles (170 km²). While the territory straddles two counties, the initial phases of what was supposed to be a bustling hub were planned for the Clark County side of the line. Geographically, Coyote Springs is pinned between [U.S. Route 93](/U.S._Route_93_in_Nevada) to the west and the rugged spine of the [Meadow Valley Mountains](/Meadow_Valley_Mountains) to the east. The location is, with a certain irony, less than an hour’s drive from the relentless neon glow of the [City of Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas) and the [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip), making its profound emptiness all the more striking.

The Coyote Springs valley itself is scarred by several major [washes](/Arroyo_(creek)), including the Pahrangat Wash and the Kane Springs Wash—natural conduits for water in a place where water is the most contentious subject of all. Access to this kingdom of dirt and dreams is limited, confined to U.S. Route 93 and [Route 168](/Nevada_State_Route_168). For the sake of bureaucratic neatness, it even has a ZIP Code: 89067, assigned to a place with no mail to deliver.

### History

Before it was a developer's fantasy, the land was under the stewardship of the [Bureau of Land Management](/Bureau_of_Land_Management) (BLM). That changed in 1988, when Congress passed the Nevada-Florida Land Exchange Authorization Act. This piece of legislation authorized a bi-coastal swap: approximately 29,000 acres of BLM land in the Coyote Springs Valley, along with another 10,000 acres in Mineral County, Nevada, were traded for about 5,000 acres of privately-owned, environmentally sensitive land in the [Florida Everglades](/Everglades). The owner of the Florida parcel was the [Aerojet Corporation](/Aerojet).

The stated purpose of this exchange was noble enough—protecting habitats for species covered by the [Endangered Species Act](/Endangered_Species_Act_of_1973) in Florida. Critically, the United States government conveyed the Nevada lands to Aerojet in [fee simple](/Fee_simple), imposing no restrictions on their future use. Aerojet’s initial plan was to utilize a fraction of the land—about 2,700 acres—to build facilities for rocket manufacturing, assembly, and testing. The rockets were never built.

The land's journey through the world of high-stakes real estate began. Aerojet sold the parcels to Harrich Investments LLC in 1996. Two years later, in 1998, Harrich sold the Coyote Springs parcel to the Coyote Springs Investment group, the entity that intended to conjure a city from the dust.

The first and only sign of life appeared in 2005, with the start of construction on the golf course designed by [Jack Nicklaus](/Jack_Nicklaus). It opened in 2008, a lonely green jewel in a vast, empty setting.

In 2009, another ambitious project was announced for the site. [BrightSource Energy](/BrightSource_Energy) revealed plans for a 960 [MW](/Megawatt) (1,290,000 [hp](/Horsepower)) [solar thermal](/Solar_thermal) [power plant](/Power_plant), intended to be operational by 2012. Like the city itself, it was a mirage. By 2011, ground had not been broken, and the start date was pushed to 2014 for its first stage and 2015 for the second. By December 2013, the only energy being generated was in a courtroom, where Brighthouse and Coyote Springs were locked in a dispute over costs after the project collapsed.

For years, the site was powered by generators. It wasn't until 2012 that a permanent electricity substation was opened, a monument of infrastructure with no community to serve.

The official groundbreaking for the residential community was held on July 5, 2006. It was a ceremony of pure optimism. Construction, however, was immediately bogged down by regulatory hurdles over water rights and environmental impact. Then the Great Recession hit, freezing development plans across the country. At Coyote Springs, the pause became permanent, exacerbated by a series of vicious legal battles between the project's owners. As of September 2016, not a single home had been built.

### Legal issues

The story of Coyote Springs is inseparable from its legal entanglements. It has been a lightning rod for controversy, fueled by grave environmental concerns and persistent allegations of political cronyism benefiting its chief architect, [Harvey Whittemore](/Harvey_Whittemore), through his connections to powerful figures like Senator [Harry Reid](/Harry_Reid). Whittemore's career as the project's champion ended in 2012, when he was convicted on three felony charges for making illegal campaign donations to Reid.

The internal dynamics of the development group were just as fraught. In 2010, Whittemore had a spectacular split from his business partners, Thomas Seeno and Albert Seeno, Jr. He resigned from the Wingfield Holding Group and sold his stake in Coyote Springs amidst accusations from the Seenos that he had embezzled company funds, partly to prop up the troubled [Whittemore Peterson Institute](/Whittemore_Peterson_Institute). Whittemore fired back with a countersuit. The legal warfare didn't stop there, as Wingfield and its partner Pardee Homes also became entangled in their own court battles.

Meanwhile, environmental groups were mounting their own offensive. In February 2009, the [Center for Biological Diversity](/Center_for_Biological_Diversity) declared its intent to sue the [United States Fish and Wildlife Service](/United_States_Fish_and_Wildlife_Service) and the Bureau of Land Management (BLM). The lawsuit alleged violations of the Endangered Species Act, arguing that the Coyote Springs development—and its massive water consumption—would devastate the local habitat, harming the threatened [desert tortoise](/Desert_tortoise) and pushing the endangered [moapa dace](/Moapa_dace) closer to extinction. The Fish and Wildlife Service and Nevada's water authority could only respond that they, too, were interested in protecting the moapa dace, a tiny fish residing in the Muddy River, whose fate had become entwined with a multi-billion dollar real estate venture.

The final chapter was written not by developers or lawyers, but by a state regulator. In May 2018, Nevada's state water engineer, Jason King, effectively halted Coyote Springs by blocking its water permits. This decision was reaffirmed in 2020, when the state water department reiterated its restrictions on groundwater pumping, declaring that any new development would place a "significant strain on the area's limited water resources." The developers sued, of course. But in January 2024, the Nevada State Supreme Court upheld the legality of the water restrictions, delivering the final, decisive blow. The desert, it seems, gets to keep its water.

